To-Link is a full-scale community lifestyle web application designed to improve relationships between neighbors by providing a unified platform that integrates social networking, task collaboration (quests), marketplace functionality, local services, booking systems, and building-related tools. The system must be built as a maintainable, modular full-stack web application using real APIs and databases, without relying on browser local storage except where absolutely unavoidable. The codebase must follow a clean architecture that ensures that modifying one feature does not unintentionally affect unrelated features.
The entire website must follow a consistent design system using a modern, high-end, clean UI style with orange as the primary theme color (similar to how Facebook uses blue or WhatsApp uses green). The layout must be non-scrollable at the page level, meaning the main viewport should always fit within the screen size, while scrolling is only allowed inside specific containers (such as posts, chat lists, or content sections). The UI must be responsive and work on both desktop and mobile devices. All loading states must use a spinning animation indicator, and all actions must have proper success and error feedback messages.
The sidebar navigation must include the following top-level categories in order: Home, Posts, Nearby, Connections, Activities, Building, Settings, Info, and Sign Out. Posts must include sub-pages for All, Sharing, 2nd Hand, Lost & Find, and Quests. Nearby includes Nearby Shops and Nearby Communities. Connections includes Messages and Friends. Activities includes Events, Calendar, and Booking Status. Building includes Facilities, AI Chat, and Documents. Settings includes Website Settings, Profile Settings, Light/Dark Mode toggle, Font Size selection (S/M/B/L), and Language switch (English and Traditional Chinese). Info includes App Feedback, Community Feedback, FAQ, Help Center, About Us, Privacy Policy, Terms of Service, and Version display.
The authentication system must include login, registration, and password reset via email. Registration must collect first name, last name, email, phone number, HKID or personal ID, country, current state (worker/employee/jobless/student), and job title (conditionally shown). After registration, all user information must be stored and reflected in profile settings.
The posts system must support four types: Sharing, 2nd Hand, Lost & Find, and Quests. Users must be able to filter posts by All, My Posts, or Other Users’ Posts. Each post must support title (max 100 characters), description (max 2000 characters), and comments (max 500 characters). Users can like posts (one like per user), comment unlimitedly, edit posts (with an “edited” label), and delete posts with a confirmation countdown (3 → 2 → 1 before enabling delete). Deleted posts must be moved into a history section in profile settings.
The quest system is one of the core features and must support a full lifecycle. Quest states include Open, Accepted, Due Soon (within 24 hours before deadline), Overdue (after deadline), Completed, and Failed. When a quest is created, it can include title, description, tags (max 10), time range (or no limit), images (max 5), and videos (max 3). When a user accepts a quest, the quest no longer expires automatically, but the accepter must complete it before the defined deadline. The system must send a reminder notification 24 hours before the deadline. If the quest is not completed by the deadline, both the accepter and the owner receive an overdue notification. The owner can then either extend the deadline or mark the quest as failed. The owner is not allowed to mark a quest as failed before the deadline. If marked as failed, the accepter receives a penalty including reward point deduction and a temporary restriction on accepting new quests (24 hours initially, increasing progressively to 48 hours, 72 hours, and so on for repeated failures). All quest actions must be logged. If the owner does not respond after the deadline, the system should send reminders and eventually auto-handle the situation after prolonged inactivity.
The messaging system must function like modern chat applications (e.g., WhatsApp or Instagram), with a list of chat rooms on the left and messages on the right. It must support direct messages, group chat (minimum 3 users), and special system-generated messages for events such as quest applications or trades. Users must be able to navigate directly to chat rooms from multiple system actions (e.g., accepting a quest or contacting a seller).
The booking system must allow users to book facilities, shops, and events. Booking requests must have statuses: Pending, Accepted, Denied, and Canceled. Owners can accept or deny bookings and must provide a reason for denial. Booking details must include usage, contact numbers (1–3), participants, organizer name, date and time, and additional information. All confirmed bookings must automatically be added to the calendar system.
The calendar system must support three event types: Booking, Joined Events (from community participation), and Personal Events (user-created). Users must be able to view, create, and manage events across different dates, and events must display full details when selected.
The Nearby system must include both list view and map view. It must use real GPS location from the browser and display nearby shops and communities. It must allow searching and sorting (e.g., nearest first). Map functionality must use a real API such as Mapbox. Each location must show full details including name, description, contact information, and additional content like announcements or events.
The file upload system must support images (JPG, JPEG, PNG, WEBP, max 5MB each) and videos (MP4 only, max 50MB each). A maximum of 5 images and 3 videos is allowed per post. Storage must use a free cloud option such as Firebase Storage.
The system must support real-time features including chat and notifications. Firebase (Firestore or Realtime Database) is recommended as the free backend solution for real-time functionality. Weather data must use a free API such as OpenWeatherMap.
The notification system must distinguish between critical notifications (which cannot be disabled, such as quest completion, booking status, and system alerts) and optional notifications (such as messages, likes, and friend requests, which users can configure in settings).
The block system must prevent all future interactions between users, including messages, posts, quests, and requests, but must preserve historical data (e.g., past conversations). Unblocking restores interaction capability.
The admin system must support report handling, warnings, and bans. Users can report others for issues such as spam or inappropriate content. Admins can review reports and choose to ignore, warn, or ban a user. The warning system must track user behavior, and after three warnings, a user may be temporarily banned. Admins must also be able to permanently ban users if necessary.
The AI Chat system must use Copilot (or equivalent) and allow users to ask questions related to building, community, or general queries. Each user is limited to 20 AI queries per day, and the UI must display a counter showing remaining questions, with warnings when nearing the limit.
The system must include comprehensive error handling. Every user action (e.g., booking, uploading, posting) must show appropriate loading indicators, success messages, or error messages if something fails (e.g., “Upload failed, please try again”).
Overall, the system must be modular, scalable, and built using real APIs and services, with a strong focus on consistent UI/UX, clear user flows, detailed interaction rules, and handling of edge cases.


